{{lead too short|date=November 2015}} {{Infobox military conflict | conflict = | width = | partof = the [[Dirty War]] | image = | caption = Alfonsín during the 1987 military rebellion | date = April, 1987 | place = [[Argentina]] | coordinates = | map_type = | map_relief = | latitude = | longitude = | map_size = | map_marksize = | map_caption = | map_label = | territory = | result = Government victory | status = | combatants_header = | combatant1 = {{Flagicon|ARG}} [[Argentine Army]] | combatant2 = {{Flagicon|ARG}} [[Carapintadas]] | combatant3 = | commander1 = {{Flagicon|ARG}} [[Raúl Alfonsín]] | commander2 = {{Flagicon|ARG}} [[Aldo Rico]] | commander3 = | units1 = | units2 = | units3 = | strength1 = | strength2 = | strength3 = | casualties1 = | casualties2 = | casualties3 = | notes = | campaignbox = }} The '''1987 Carapintada mutiny''' took place in [[Argentina]], during the presidency of [[Raúl Alfonsín]].
==Context== The [[Dirty War]] took place in Argentina during the 1970s and the early 1980s. Left-wing guerrillas, such as [[Montoneros]] and [[People's Revolutionary Army (Argentina)|ERP]], sought to establish a socialist dictatorship, as in Cuba. The military, first during the civilian governments of [[Juan Perón]] and [[Isabel Martínez de Perón]], and then during the [[National Reorganization Process]] military dictatorship, sought to prevent that. The military defeated the guerrillas, but committed human rights violations during the conflict. New elections were held in 1983, and [[Raúl Alfonsín]] became the new president.<ref>Lewis, pp. 134–146</ref>
The [[National Commission on the Disappearance of Persons]] prepared the "Nunca más" report ({{lang-es|Never again}}), detailing 8,961 cases of forced disappearances. The [[Trial of the Juntas]] sentenced the heads of the military dictatorship, and the [[full stop law]] caused an increased number of charges against the military.<ref name="Lewis154" />
==The mutiny== [[File:Felices pascuas 2.jpg|thumb|left|[[Raúl Alfonsín]] announces the end of the mutiny.]] The Major [[Ernesto Barreiro]] was indicted, but refused to appear in the court. He started a mutiny in Córdoba in April 14, rallying troops to support him. Three days later, Lieutenant Colonel [[Aldo Rico]] started another mutiny in [[Campo de Mayo]], [[Buenos Aires]], supporting Barreiro. They were called "[[Carapintadas]]" ({{lang-es|Painted faces}}) because they practiced [[military camouflage]].<ref>Hedges, p. 248</ref> They asked for new authorities in the armed forces, and an end to the dirty war related trials.<ref name="Lewis154">Lewis, P. 154</ref>
The loyal military units surrounded the rebels, but refused to attack them. The population made demonstrations in support of Alfonsín, and the [[General Confederation of Labour (Argentina)|CGT]] union called on a general strike on his behalf until the crisis was resolved. Other unions, political parties, industrial sectors and the Church manifested their support for Alfonsín as well.<ref>Lewis, pp. 154–155</ref>
Alfonsín personally led the negotiations with the rebels. The mutiny was stopped, and Alfonsín announced it in the balcony of the ''[[Casa Rosada]]'', to the people gathered there. In the following weeks he made changes to the command of the armed forces, and sent the [[Law of Due Obedience]] bill to the Congress. This law, complementing the full stop law, prevented hundreds of prosecutions.<ref>Lewis, p. 155</ref> The minister [[Horacio Jaunarena]] clarified that the law was a project previous to the mutiny, and that the new authorities in the armed forces were not the ones requested by Rico.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.clarin.com/politica/negociacion-nombro-generales-queria-Rico_0_467953340.html|title= Carapintadas en Semana Santa: "No hubo negociación ni se nombró a ninguno de los generales que quería Rico"|trans_title= Carapintadas in easter eve: "there was no negotiation, nor generals suggested by Rico"|language= Spanish|author= Silvana Boschi|date= April 23, 2011|publisher= Clarín|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref>
